        <div class="current article z-20 bg-green-50 dark:bg-gray-800 text-green-800 dark:text-gray-200 col-span-8 sm:col-span-6 p-4 min-h-screen h-full text-lg py-16 md:p-24 lg:px-48">
            <h1 class="font-display font-semibold text-4xl sm:py-6 lg: py-10">Honeycomb Soap</h1>
            <span class="block text-right -mt-8">Jan 22, 2021</span></br>
            <article class="text-green-800 dark:text-gray-200">
            

<p>My roommate and I made these soap bars.</p>

<a href="../../static/img/soap/r0.png"> <img style="display:none" src="../../static/img/soap/ld/r0.png"><img src="../../static/img/soap/r0.png" alt="soap bars" style="background-image: url('../../static/img/soap/ld/r0.png')"></img></a>

<a href="../../static/img/soap/r1.png"> <img style="display:none" src="../../static/img/soap/ld/r1.png"><img src="../../static/img/soap/r1.png" alt="soap bars" style="background-image: url('../../static/img/soap/ld/r1.png')"></img></a>

</br>
<p>Soapmaking is a rewarding hobby because you can personalize the recipe and mold to make a unique and useful product. We used what's called 'the cold process' of making soap.</p>
<p>The oil is 80% olive and 20% coconut oil. We thought of making traditional Marseille soap which is made from 100% olive oil, but added some coconut for extra strength and lather. For aromas, we used a lot of citrus peel oil and lavender etheric oil. We also dried and powdered mandarin peels and added them to the mix. The olive oil creates a nice yellow-greenish base color, but we did mix in inert mineral dyes like iron oxide, French ochre and ultramarine.</p>
<p>Having spent a lot on ingredients already, I was looking for a cheap hexagonal mold. One day I literally stumbled upon it on a bike path, in the form of a plastic gravel stabilizer plate which can be found in construction stores. For added honeycomb structure we put the mold on top of bubble wrap.</p>

